>>In Great Britain, a 2.0 L Type 4 engine was fitted by Arthur Baraclough
>>into his 1970 VW Type 2. I believe he used the standard crankshaft driven
>>fan, but did have to modify the engine bay surround. This van travelled
>>about 250,000 miles through several deserts, over mountain ranges and is
>>now reputed to be in the Peter Black Museum, in Yorkshire.
>>
>>His van has many inovative features (including exhaust-heated, domestic
>>hot water system, double glazed windows and engine starting handle), all
>>of which Arthur fitted himself.
>>
>>Sadly, he died in mid-1996, at the age of about 83, having driven his van
>>almost upto the time of his death. I corresponded with him briefly, during
>>late 1995 and early 1996, shortly after I joined the British VW Type 2
>>Owners Club, which currently has about 2,500 fully paid up members.
>>
>>Regards.
>>
>>        Nigel A. Skeet


